che.jpg</a>. --></p>\n      </li>\n      \n    </ol></div>","id":"e503d6cd-40ad-5238-9e81-3f1fd77d864a","frontmatter":{"date":"October 23, 2020","description":null,"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"7ef71ed4-1390-5169-8364-90c50ce9086a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/amphibious-buildings/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Amphibious Buildings"}}},{"node":{"id":"22c6ace5-a0f2-5bec-abaf-8db95e75a9fd","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/barrier-islands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Barrier Islands"}}},{"node":{"id":"ae5a1f35-fce3-53ea-84cb-05783ff86dca","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/beach-nourishment/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Beach Nourishment"}}},{"node":{"id":"6e12f862-8323-5f7a-991e-aee66741ab3d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/breakwaters/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Breakwaters"}}},{"node":{"id":"733c0edd-ab23-5a79-8b92-0a0a3fa66af0","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/coastal-wetlands/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Coastal Wetlands"}}},{"node":{"id":"87e855d9-52ea-59bf-aedb-ccfe76a3df51","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-permits/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Permits"}}},{"node":{"id":"778be613-c456-5c81-b08b-d5515ae38ed9","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/development-transfers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Development Transfers"}}},{"node":{"id":"ea68ab98-acb3-5f86-bec1-7afa36349ca6","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dikes"}}},{"node":{"id":"8043b7a4-55d4-52a5-b9db-5b8a3e6c4bf6","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dry-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Dry Floodproofing"}}},{"node":{"id":"a8c82117-3f24-5832-ab8e-25826bf319e2","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/dune-building-restoration/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Dune Building / Restoration"}}},{"node":{"id":"0623976c-4c91-537d-a14b-2fc349d00999","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/easement-and-covenants/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Easement and Covenants"}}},{"node":{"id":"8a0c019c-f4f9-5197-be93-c8e22506f97b","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/emergency-planning-and-preparedness/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Emergency Planning Preparedness"}}},{"node":{"id":"1f64f01d-8737-5cfe-973b-fee09a2ac91a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/evacuation-routes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Evacuation Routes"}}},{"node":{"id":"f95c5798-23c9-5107-bc5b-41c0bee3130f","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/floodwalls/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Floodwalls"}}},{"node":{"id":"2c782d6a-3e20-57d7-b88b-b28de7276c44","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/foreshore-tenure/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Foreshore Tenure"}}},{"node":{"id":"38db4e60-391a-5185-ac1d-505dffafd4ae","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/groynes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Groynes"}}},{"node":{"id":"1c92479b-69fb-5d6e-832f-715a1c4e6a13","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-acquisition/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Acquisition"}}},{"node":{"id":"11929fb9-bb5f-51fe-8be7-7725ae226fab","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/land-trust/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Land Trust"}}},{"node":{"id":"af206efc-f67c-5b26-a7d4-afefe2fc660c","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/protected-area-zoning/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Avoid","title":"Protected Area Zoning"}}},{"node":{"id":"1678f2e8-7dea-5a35-9e4f-7c258acc512d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/reef-systems/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Reef Systems"}}},{"node":{"id":"f578c06a-426e-5ad3-9d4a-062a6cd6c531","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/scour-protection/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Scour Protection"}}},{"node":{"id":"9886ab9a-0409-5f42-b606-4da1f6b5606d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/seawall/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Seawall"}}},{"node":{"id":"e503d6cd-40ad-5238-9e81-3f1fd77d864a","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Secondary Dikes"}}},{"node":{"id":"35be0a4c-5325-585d-a143-1433d7cbd5b5","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/storm-surge-barriers/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Protect","title":"Storm Surge Barriers"}}},{"node":{"id":"b9524640-c924-53b8-a087-f5a144c3ad9d","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/subdivision-regulation-and-development-control/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Retreat","title":"Subdivision Regulation and Development Control"}}},{"node":{"id":"9d50eddd-7656-5a4d-b75b-5887ea8ad5be","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Warning System"}}},{"node":{"id":"a6e87138-5a0d-5dc6-afe8-678a851a6028","fields":{"slug":"/strategies/wet-floodproofing/"},"frontmatter":{"strategyTypes":"Accommodate","title":"Wet Floodproofing"}}}]}},"pageContext":{"animationSlug":"//strategies/secondary-dikes/animation.*png/","slug":"/strategies/secondary-dikes/","foo":"bar","subpages":{"benefits":"<ul>\n<li>Serves to intercept flood runoff and sediment from exposed disturbed areas, such as a newly-constructed road or slope, and filter sediment. </li>\n<li>Redirects the flood water to a slope drain, sediment basin, or other specified location.</li>\n<li>Intercepts runoff from undisturbed upland areas, and redirects runoff to a sediment\nbasin or specified location. <sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup></li>\n<li>Limits flooding to areas that are less developed which helps to protect more developed areas.</li>\n</ul>","examples":["<h3>Hondsbossche Zeewering Sleeper Dike</h3>\n<h4>Holland, The Netherlands</h4>\n<p>In 1526, a secondary dike was constructed behind the Hondsbossche Zeewering Dike because of concerns related to the weakness of the sea wall.<sup id=\"fnref-3\"><a href=\"#fn-3\" class=\"footnote-ref\">3</a></sup> In 1570, the main dike was breached, and the secondary dike prevented North Holland from being flooded. Secondary dikes or sleeper dikes were commonly used all over the Netherlands as part of the Delta Plan (Dutch dike system).<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> However, most of these dikes no longer have a function in flood protection after the improvement of the Delta Plan but remain protected today for their cultural and historical value.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup></p>","<h3>Terra Nova Secondary Dike</h3>\n<h4>Richmond BC, Canada</h4>\n<p>As part of the Richmond Dike Master Plan, the City of Richmond British Columbia is considering an alternative dike alignment in the Terra Nova area. As an alternative, the Dike Master Plan identifies the alignment to be set inland as part of a secondary dike. The dike is intended to protect sensitive assets such as private homes and heritage sites while less sensitive assets such as parks, trails, and open spaces can be flooded, in the case of a breach.<sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup></p>"],"challenges":"<ul>\n<li>Must be designed and constructed to mitigate erosion caused by water diversion and concentrated runoff flow. </li>\n<li>For construction, topographical features such as space, degree of slope, and access can be limiting or prohibitive factors <sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","images":["<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/604ec/Figure1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 34.08360128617363%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"image\"\n        title=\"image\"\n        src=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/fcda8/Figure1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/12f09/Figure1.png 148w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/e4a3f/Figure1.png 295w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/fcda8/Figure1.png 590w,\n/living-breakwaters-web/static/7ab322fcb2d9a853e90983f25950a121/604ec/Figure1.png 622w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\nSleeper Dike near the Hondsbossche Zeewering <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>"],"summary":"<p>Secondary dikes work in conjunction with primary dikes to reduce the impact of a flood if the primary dike is breached.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> Several secondary dikes designs may be similar to that of a primary dike but on a smaller scale. For example, in the city of Winnipeg, and secondary dike is simply defined as <strong>(any permanent dyke or other flood control work within the City of Winnipeg which has been, or is, constructed between a primary dyke and the channel)</strong>. Hence, secondary dikes are classified based on their position and the role they play in flood mitigation. In the Netherlands, secondary dikes were historically known as ‘sleeper dikes’: a backup dike which is located between the main dike and the land.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> Today, secondary dikes are still a viable adaptation strategy and are usually placed behind the main dike to protect high-value residential land in the case of a breach. In between the main dike and secondary dike are the least sensitive assets such as parks and open spaces that can withstand flooding. </p>","types":"<ul>\n<li>A <strong>berm</strong> is a ridge that is constructed from compacted soil. The dike could be made from composted material, gravel, crushed rock, sandbags, gravel bag barriers, or straw bales</li>\n<li>A <strong>temporary dike</strong> is designed to intercept and prevent runoff from entering a disturbed area It diverts or directs the water to a controlled or stabilized drainage outlet. <sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup></li>\n</ul>"},"previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/types/"},"html":"<ul>\n<li><strong>Sensor Networks for Flood Detection</strong> are used for flood detection in areas that are affected by heavy rainfall and hurricanes. </li>\n<li>In a <strong>Based and GIS-Based Flood, Warning data</strong> is collected in real-time from hydrological observation stations. The data is then processed  by a centralized computer system and results are sent to a client computer in a  control room via remote access.</li>\n<li><strong>Flood Warning based on Radio, SMS, TVs, and Phones</strong> use a microcontroller from the “ARM family, a Marvell 88F6281 and the Unix FreeBSD interface and integrated database.” Hydrological data is then sent in real-time for decision making via radio communication. <sup id=\"fnref-11\"><a href=\"#fn-11\" class=\"footnote-ref\">11</a></sup></li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":""}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/strategies/warning-system/example1/"},"html":"<h3>Cyclone Warning System</h3>\n<h4>Bangladesh</h4>\n<p>Historically, Bangladesh has been an active area for tropical cyclones. Unfortunately, a lack of protective measures has resulted in high death and casualty rates.<sup id=\"fnref-4\"><a href=\"#fn-4\" class=\"footnote-ref\">4</a></sup> As an adaptation response, Bangladesh implemented the Cyclone Preparedness Programme (CPP) which focuses on infrastructure development, an early warning system, and cyclone shelters.<sup id=\"fnref-5\"><a href=\"#fn-5\" class=\"footnote-ref\">5</a></sup> The warning system consists of three components: monitoring, evaluation, and response and draws data from multiple sources.<sup id=\"fnref-6\"><a href=\"#fn-6\" class=\"footnote-ref\">6</a></sup> The warning system has proven to be successful during the 1970, 1991 and 2007 cyclones which resulted in fewer deaths.<sup id=\"fnref-7\"><a href=\"#fn-7\" class=\"footnote-ref\">7</a></sup></p>","frontmatter":{"title":""}}}}}